de decisions embedded within families. Even after the war, sole survivors often described their losses and rebuilt their lives with a distinct focus on family. Yet this perspective is lacking in academic analyses. In this work, scholars from the United States, Israel, and across Europe bring a variety of backgrounds and disciplines to their study of the Holocaust and its aftermath from the family perspective. Drawing on research from Belarus to Great Britain, and examining both Jewish and Romani families, they demonstrate the importance of recognizing how people continued to function within family units—broadly defined—throughout the war and afterward.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aHolocaust survivorsvBiography. 0aHolocaust victims' familiesxHistoryy20th century. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)vBiography. 0aJewish familiesxHistoryy20th century. 0aRomaniesxNazi persecution. 0aWar and families. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xInfluence. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aJewish Studies, Human Rights, History, Race, Ethnic Studies, Women's Studies, Anthropology, HISTORY Holocaust Genocide, Political Science, Emigration, Immigration, Jewish, Cultural, SOCIAL SCIENCE, Belarus, Great Britain, Testimonies, memoirs, Families, War, Survivors, United States, Israel, Romani families, Jewish Families.1 aAdler, Eliyana R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAdler, Eliyana R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAleksiun, Natalia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBanyai, Viktoria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBartash, Volha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBányai, Viktória, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCapková, Ka